english:
  title: Epitaph for Kim Gun, Former Censor and Keeper of Balance
  author: Choe Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    People of the East are by nature indolent, and do not apply themselves to learning to cultivate their character. Thus some pursue worldly advancement merely to feed and clothe their families—which the common man may do, yet it falls short of the gentleman's way. When it comes to discerning righteousness and examining one's place in the world, few refuse to let the judgments of others determine their honor or shame. How much more so in these declining times, when scholars lack firm conviction, chasing fortune and fleeing calamity, playing master when fortune smiles and servant when it frowns. To walk the middle path in such an age, to stand alone and unbending in one's bearing—surely such a man deserves the name of upright scholar. Such was Kim Gun of Ugyesan.

    Kim was the youngest son of the celebrated scholar Dunchonjigong. When the Crown Prince later became King, Dunchon served as tutor, bringing his two sons to court. The King showed special affection to young Kim, treating him with uncommon courtesy. Later, when the King ascended the throne, he appointed Kim to the post of Censor, then promoted him to Vice Director of the Bureau of Records. All expected great things of him, this old servant and man of talent.

    But fortune turned against him. A matter of business offended one of the corrupt eunuchs at court, and Kim was banished to a distant island. For years he endured hardship and struggle, yet bore it with serene acceptance, as one resigned to fate. When he returned, he withdrew to his garden at home. When guests came, he would set out wine, play the zither, compose poems, and amuse himself—no longer troubled by thoughts of office and rank. Fifteen years passed in this manner.

    Then in the year of Bingchuk, when the King returned from the capital determined to set things right, he recalled Kim to court, appointing him Counselor and Keeper of Balance. Against his inclination, Kim accepted and served several months. The officials and scholars took hope that corruption might be cleansed. But a powerful minister from the court abused his influence, showing contempt for our scholars and even imprisoning censors in the palace dungeons. When Kim remonstrated with the King, his words grew passionate and his manner fierce. For this, he was attacked and disgraced. He then feigned illness and withdrew from office, returning to his home as before.

    Those who had suffered injustice found no redress, and good men could only sigh in sorrow at his departure. Last autumn, he fell ill, but seemed to recover without treatment. But last month the illness returned, and within a single day, he passed from this world.

    Alas! Kim possessed a firm and upright nature. In poetry and calligraphy, he followed the family tradition. In his dealings with men, he was constant in sincerity—the longer you knew him, the more you dared not take liberties. Some say his ideals were set too high, unwilling to bend even slightly, and thus his career came to this. Yet such is the judgment of common men, not the measure by which to judge Kim.

    When a scholar is born into this world, some meet opportunity and some do not. Those who meet it see their way flourish and their influence spread widely. Those who do not see their person withdraw and their inner completeness remain whole. So whether one meets opportunity or not rests with the fortune or misfortune of others—what loss or gain can it bring to oneself?

    Kim's courtesy name was Wongwi and his given name was Seojung, later changed to Gaemul. He once took the civil service examination but did not pass, and took the name Ugyesan as his literary name. His family was originally from Uiseong County in Bokju. His grandfather achieved the rank of Inspector. His father, the renowned Dunchon, reached the position of Minister of Literature. His mother was Lady Lee, daughter of the Inspector. Kim was married twice and had one son and five daughters. His son Seom holds the position of Vice Inspector of the Bureau of Calligraphy. His daughters were married to officials. Two younger daughters remained at home.

    Kim was born in the tenth month of the year Gyeyu in the reign of Zhiyuan, and passed away in the second month of the year Jeongmyo of Taideng era, and was buried in the third month of that same year, his grave marked on a hillside.

    Kim did not treat me as an ordinary scholar, but commanded his son to come study under my guidance. Therefore I reverently compose this epitaph:

    What lies within our power—learning, action—
    these are ours to master.
    What lies beyond—rank and lifespan—
    these are heaven's domain.

    Only the gentleman grasps what is his to command
    and strives with full force,
    releasing what is beyond his reach
    and entrusts it to heaven.

    Ah, Ugyesan—
    what more could you desire?
  footnotes:
    - Ugyesan (愚溪) was Kim Gun's literary name, meaning 'Valley of Folly.' The name reflects his philosophical stance of humble acceptance despite his learning and virtue.
    - Dunchon (鈍村) refers to Kim Gun's father, whose name suggests rustic simplicity, reflecting the Confucian ideal of the unworldly sage.
    - The epitaph reflects the political instability of the Goryeo-Yuan period, when Korean officials faced pressure from powerful Chinese court factions.
    - 'The final poem presents the Confucian and Daoist philosophy central to the work: acceptance of fate while striving virtuously within one''s control.'
